bodily composition was incompatible with visceral inequality or racism. While ‘race’ had not assumed its modern valence, and ‘racial’ ideologies were still to come, such typecasting nonetheless had mundane, lasting consequences. Grounded in humoral physiology, and Christian universalism notwithstanding, bodily prejudices inflected social stratification, domestic politics, sectarian division and international relations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDiscriminationzEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aDiscriminationzEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 0aPhysical anthropologyzEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aPhysical anthropologyzEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 0aRacismzEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aRacismzEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 17th Century.2bisacsh  aClass.  aColonisation.  aEthnicity.  aHealth.  aHuman body.  aHumoralism.  aMigration.  aMonogenesis.  aNationalism.  aRacism.1 aDawson, Mark S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2019 eBook-Packagez978311128249740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152613449340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526134493423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526134493/original  a978-3-11-128249-7  Manchester University Press 2019 eBook-Packageb2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles